<section class="container py-4">
  <div class="row g-5">

    <!-- ── Main column ──────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <div class="col-lg-8">

      <p class="lead" style="color:#ccc;">A research abstract is a reader's first — and often only — encounter with your work. This course familiarises you with the genre conventions of scientific research abstracts so that you can analyse existing abstracts critically and write your own with confidence.</p>

      <!-- Transformation demo -->
      <div class="sra-demo mt-4">

        <div class="sra-demo-header">
          <div class="d-flex align-items-center gap-3 flex-wrap">
            <h3 class="mb-0">Abstract Transformation</h3>
            <span id="sa-badge" class="sa-badge sa-badge-draft">First Draft</span>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-2 mb-0">Watch a weak first draft become a strong abstract — one criterion at a time. Click the abstract to advance, or wait 2&nbsp;seconds.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- 2-second progress bar -->
        <div class="sra-progress-wrap">
          <div id="sa-progress-bar" class="sra-progress-bar"></div>
        </div>

        <!-- ── Hidden stage data ─────────────────────────────────────── -->
        <div id="sa-stages" style="display:none" aria-hidden="true">

          <div data-label="First Draft" data-badge-class="sa-badge-draft" data-criterion=""
               data-annotation="A typical first draft — vague sentences, no named methods, and no measurable claims. Every sentence will be improved in the steps that follow.">
            <p>This paper is about a virtual reality system for language learning. The system includes a virtual agent that users can speak to. Understanding how people feel when speaking in a foreign language is important for adapting such systems. The aim was to study how speaking in a first language and a foreign language affects participants differently. Before the study, some educators were consulted about the design of the system. A study was conducted with some participants who spoke in two languages. Various data were collected during the study using sensors. Participants found the system useful and responded positively to speaking with the virtual agent. The results have potential implications for language education.</p>
          </div>

          <div data-label="Novelty" data-badge-class="sa-badge-novelty" data-criterion="novelty"
               data-annotation="The opening three sentences are rewritten to identify the research gap — the missing link between biosignal signatures and foreign language anxiety in VR systems. The word &quot;however&quot; (sentence 3) signals the gap directly. Orange marks the new text.">
            <p><span class="sra-c-novelty">Conversational practice is essential for language fluency, yet in many contexts access to speaking partners remains limited. An embodied virtual agent (EVA) in virtual reality (VR) offers an on-demand alternative. However, adapting these systems to learner affect requires understanding the biosignal signatures of foreign language anxiety (FLA).</span> The aim was to study how speaking in a first language and a foreign language affects participants differently. Before the study, some educators were consulted about the design of the system. A study was conducted with some participants who spoke in two languages. Various data were collected during the study using sensors. Participants found the system useful and responded positively to speaking with the virtual agent. The results have potential implications for language education.</p>
          </div>

          <div data-label="Purpose" data-badge-class="sa-badge-purpose" data-criterion=""
               data-annotation="The vague aim sentence is replaced with a precise purpose statement — naming the exact comparison (L1 vs L2), the outcome measures (anxiety, presence, arousal), and the sensors used (PPG, eye tracking). Purple marks the new text.">
            <p><span class="sra-c-novelty">Conversational practice is essential for language fluency, yet in many contexts access to speaking partners remains limited. An embodied virtual agent (EVA) in virtual reality (VR) offers an on-demand alternative. However, adapting these systems to learner affect requires understanding the biosignal signatures of foreign language anxiety (FLA).</span> <span class="sra-c-purpose">We present a VR system in which participants converse with an EVA and examine how native (L1) versus foreign (L2) conversation differentially affects self-reported anxiety, sense of presence, and physiological arousal measured via photoplethysmography (PPG) and eye tracking.</span> Before the study, some educators were consulted about the design of the system. A study was conducted with some participants who spoke in two languages. Various data were collected during the study using sensors. Participants found the system useful and responded positively to speaking with the virtual agent. The results have potential implications for language education.</p>
          </div>

          <div data-label="Rigour" data-badge-class="sa-badge-rigour" data-criterion="rigour"
               data-annotation="The two vague method sentences are replaced with concrete detail: a pre-study focus group (3 educators), a within-subjects design, N = 40, and named sensors. Blue marks the new text.">
            <p><span class="sra-c-novelty">Conversational practice is essential for language fluency, yet in many contexts access to speaking partners remains limited. An embodied virtual agent (EVA) in virtual reality (VR) offers an on-demand alternative. However, adapting these systems to learner affect requires understanding the biosignal signatures of foreign language anxiety (FLA).</span> <span class="sra-c-purpose">We present a VR system in which participants converse with an EVA and examine how native (L1) versus foreign (L2) conversation differentially affects self-reported anxiety, sense of presence, and physiological arousal measured via photoplethysmography (PPG) and eye tracking.</span> <span class="sra-c-rigour">A pre-study focus group with three experienced language educators informed EVA design and task selection. In a within-subjects study (N = 40), participants completed conversational tasks while physiological data were recorded via PPG and eye-tracking sensors.</span> Various data were collected during the study using sensors. Participants found the system useful and responded positively to speaking with the virtual agent. The results have potential implications for language education.</p>
          </div>

          <div data-label="Substance" data-badge-class="sa-badge-substance" data-criterion="substance"
               data-annotation="The single vague results sentence is replaced with a p-value, a specific comparison, and six named physiological measures. These numbers are what make the finding credible and non-trivial. Green marks the new text.">
            <p><span class="sra-c-novelty">Conversational practice is essential for language fluency, yet in many contexts access to speaking partners remains limited. An embodied virtual agent (EVA) in virtual reality (VR) offers an on-demand alternative. However, adapting these systems to learner affect requires understanding the biosignal signatures of foreign language anxiety (FLA).</span> <span class="sra-c-purpose">We present a VR system in which participants converse with an EVA and examine how native (L1) versus foreign (L2) conversation differentially affects self-reported anxiety, sense of presence, and physiological arousal measured via photoplethysmography (PPG) and eye tracking.</span> <span class="sra-c-rigour">A pre-study focus group with three experienced language educators informed EVA design and task selection. In a within-subjects study (N = 40), participants completed conversational tasks while physiological data were recorded via PPG and eye-tracking sensors.</span> <span class="sra-c-substance">L2 conversation elicited significantly higher state anxiety than L1 (p &lt; .001), while sense of presence remained comparable across conditions. Across windowed HRV and eye tracking, six physiological measures showed significant L1&ndash;L2 differences in directions consistent with heightened L2 stress (BPM, MeanNN, LF, LF/HF, SampEn, and Saccade Amplitude).</span> Participants found the system useful and responded positively to speaking with the virtual agent. The results have potential implications for language education.</p>
          </div>

          <div data-label="Significance" data-badge-class="sa-badge-significance" data-criterion="significance"
               data-annotation="The final two sentences now make the significance explicit — two numbered takeaways establish what the research contributes to language learning technology and biosignal research. Teal marks the new text.">
            <p><span class="sra-c-novelty">Conversational practice is essential for language fluency, yet in many contexts access to speaking partners remains limited. An embodied virtual agent (EVA) in virtual reality (VR) offers an on-demand alternative. However, adapting these systems to learner affect requires understanding the biosignal signatures of foreign language anxiety (FLA).</span> <span class="sra-c-purpose">We present a VR system in which participants converse with an EVA and examine how native (L1) versus foreign (L2) conversation differentially affects self-reported anxiety, sense of presence, and physiological arousal measured via photoplethysmography (PPG) and eye tracking.</span> <span class="sra-c-rigour">A pre-study focus group with three experienced language educators informed EVA design and task selection. In a within-subjects study (N = 40), participants completed conversational tasks while physiological data were recorded via PPG and eye-tracking sensors.</span> <span class="sra-c-substance">L2 conversation elicited significantly higher state anxiety than L1 (p &lt; .001), while sense of presence remained comparable across conditions. Across windowed HRV and eye tracking, six physiological measures showed significant L1&ndash;L2 differences in directions consistent with heightened L2 stress (BPM, MeanNN, LF, LF/HF, SampEn, and Saccade Amplitude).</span> <span class="sra-c-significance">Participants valued the EVA&#39;s conversational initiative and perceived L2 conversation as authentic practice, though speech-recognition accuracy for L2 speech and text-to-speech naturalness in L1 remain areas for improvement. These findings establish: 1) EVA conversation in VR offers a viable paradigm for studying FLA and 2) consumer-grade PPG and eye tracking sensors provide usable proxies for cognitive load and stress.</span></p>
          </div>

        </div>
        <!-- /hidden stage data -->

        <!-- Abstract display — click to pause / resume -->
        <div class="sra-abstract-body" id="sa-abstract-wrap" title="Click to pause">
          <div id="sa-abstract"></div>
